ical leaders and his fellow historians. They look at Walter Prescott Webb’s fundamental, innovative vision as a promoter of the past and Ruthe Winegarten’s efforts to shine the spotlight on minorities and women who made history across the state. Other essayists explore Llerena Friend delving into an ambitious study of Sam Houston, Charles Ramsdell courageously addressing delicate issues such as racism and launching his controversial examination of Reconstruction in Texas, Robert Cotner—an Ohio-born product of the Ivy League—bringing a fresh perspective to the field, and Robert Maxwell engaged in early work in environmental history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHistorianszTexasvBiography. 0aHistorianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aHistoriographyzTexasxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Southwest (AZ, NM, OK, TX).2bisacsh1 aAlmaráz Jr, Félix D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Michael L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Patrick L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Patrick L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCox, Patrick l., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrimm, Carolina Castillo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendrickson Jr, Kenneth E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendrickson, Kenneth E., Kenneth E., Jr., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJones, Nancy Baker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcComb, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonal